Intellectual Merit: This University of Oklahoma (OU) Major Research Instrumentation (MRI) project has aquired and deployed all of the hardware and software components of, and will maintain until at least spring 2029, more likely until ~2031, a large scale storage instrument -- the OU & Regional Research Store (OURRstore) -- to enable OU's faculty, staff, postdocs,graduate students and undergraduates to pursue data-intensive research by building large and growing data collections, to share and publish these datasets, which they can make discoverable, and to provide this capability to all institutions in the Great Plains Network as well as in Established Program to Stimulate Competitive Research (EPSCoR) jurisdictions. Via an innovative, low cost business model, researchers buy their own tape cartridges, good for OURRstore's lifetime, and pay zero usage charges (just tape cartridges and their shipping costs). The OU Supercomputing Center for Education &Research (OSCER) leads; MRI PI Neeman is OSCER's Director. The instrument already has 159 users, after being available for ~3 3/4 years.


Via careful stewardship of grant funds, the project team has been able to substantially outstrip the originally proposed capacity, speed, reliability and lifespan of OURRstore. In particular:


* OURRStore's usable capacity in TB is expected to be more than 200% as big as originally proposed;


* OURRstore's tape speed is expected to be ~250% as fast as originally proposed;


* OURRstore's disk speed is expected to be ~900% as fast as originally proposed;


* OURRstore's reliability will be much improved, because of incorporating a second tape library at a remote location;


* OURRstore's lifespan will be extended, being decommissioned no earlier than 2029 and most likely in ~2031, instead of as early 2026 as originally proposed.


By grant end, OURRstore already had 159 users, in less than half of its lifespan.





Broader Impacts: OURRstore provides a unique capability for researchers in EPSCoR jurisdictions: An all-STEM, all-EPSCoR storage resource for large scale, long term archiving of bulk research datasets, with dual copies on separate tape cartridges, not tied to a specific allocation of compute resources, with only one-time up-front costs but no recurring charges. In fact, at the national scale, this capability is unavailable to researchers in non-EPSCoR jurisdictions. OURRstore's advisory committee includes members from every EPSCoR jurisdiction.


NOTE: EPSCoR jurisdictions in 2024: AK, AL, AR, DE, GU, HI, IA, ID, KS, KY, LA, ME, MS, MT, ND, NE, NH, NM, NV, OK, PR, RI, SC, SD, VI, VT, WV, WY.


